					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">In addition...<br /><ul><li>if the offset (in your indirect offset and indirect indexed) can only be positive, a downward growing stack is much more useful than an upward growing stack, because you can then access a stacked element with that offset;</li><li>The decision between full or empty descending is a bit of a personal choice, however a full descending stack give a useful meaning to <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">LOD R0, [SP, 0]</tt>; it accesses the first stacked element (contrast with a empty descending one, it's an invalid access, or otherwise unmeaningful). The only cost, as you mentioned, is that you initialize <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">SP</tt> to an &quot;invalid&quot; location, ex. if your stack uses words <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">$1FF</tt> downward then you initialize SP with <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">$200</tt></li></ul></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

